@graph.name: akatwengatwenge
@graph.sentence:
Thipe akweke anthurre mape, aywerte-arenye. Arne akweke mapeke
apeke arerle aw arne akngerrele apeke arrkene-irrerlenge.

Irlpelhe ikwerenhe urrperle mperlkere ahelhe-ahelhe ante akaperte athetheke.

Akaperte arle akwele atwerreke-iperre, alhwe-iperre anteme akwele impatye yanhe, kapertelearlenge.

Antywe akweke artetyerretyerre-kenhe arteke akine ikwerenhe re mpwareme. Ante aywerte kweneke ware irrperle tyerrtye mape apeke aremele.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
They are very small birds that live in the spinifex.
You see them in little trees, or even in big trees you see them playing around.
It has black wings, white and a bit of brown and its head is red.
It must have got hit on the head - the story to it that the red is the tracks of its blood on its head.
They make the same kind of little nest as the willywag tail does (like a little bag hanging in a tree). They go into the spinifex when they see people coming.
They eat little grubs and little insects and a lot of other little things that birds eat.

@graph.name: alpwertekalpwerte
@graph.sentence:
Thipe urrperle ante mperlkere, arrakerte urrperle. Arrpwere-arteke akine renhe aretyeke akwele ulkere arle re.
Itnenhenhe aretyeke, apmere putyeke aw apmere arrpenhe aneke. 
Re arlkweme kere – kelyawe, tyape akweke, intelyapelyape. Intelyapelyape akweke, ante thipele arlkwentye akngerre renhe.
Antywe ikwerenhe mpwareme arne arntarlkweke, arrpwere-arteke akine.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
This is a black and white bird with a black beak It looks a bit like a magpie  but smaller.
You see them out in the bush and everywhere else.
It eats meat lizards, little grubs and butterflies little butterflies and anything that a bird can eat.
It makes its nest in the fork of a tree like magpies do.

@graph.name: angepe
@graph.sentence:
Thipe angepe apele unte aretyeke, urrperle, alknge kwarte mperlkere. Putye-warne alhemele, atningke-anthurre arle anyente apeke, aw atherre mape apeke.
Arnterre-anthurre angkerle anerlenge. Mapele, apmere mpwaremele aneme arne akertnele anerlenge aremele. Merneke ankeyele, kereke apeke.
Putyenge mape arntarnterentye akngerre akine – thipe angepele artwe putye-arenye itne alkngarre ilemele-ileme, ‘Arlenge alhetyale kwenhe, yanhe-ketyenge kwenhe.’
Kele arelhele apeke, mape angkemele ileme, ‘Mpareye alpetyekaye, apmere-warne alpetyekeye, angepe angkemenge kwene.’ Kele itne alpemele anteme ingkerre apmere-warne.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
The crow is a black bird and its eyeball is white.
when you go out bush you see big mobs of crows – or one or two.
They talk really loud.
When people make camp he sits up the tree watching them. He wants that food and that meat.
They are caring birds - they hang around people 
and if they see something dangerous they warn you (and say), 'don't go too far from the camp, might be danger there'
Then a woman might tell people, singing out, 'let's go home, the crow is warning us about something!'
And then everyone will go home.

@graph.name: angkwene
@graph.sentence:
Thipe angkwene aretyeke mperlkere akngerre. Arne akertnele anirrirrerlenge, bore itwele, aw dam itwele apeke. Aw kwatye awenge lherele arle intemeke apeke.

Kaperte ikwerenhele ilpelhe arrirlpe tneme, pelkere-arteke akine. Wale ikwerenhe arle athetheke an untarne-untarne. Mwerre akngerre anthurre.

Itne putyeke pateyemalene ntange arlkweme ante arnengentyele ntange arlkweme atwakeye, lyeke arlke.

Apurte akwete alkereke-irreme, akngerre anthurre angkerremele.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
The Pink Cockatoo is a white bird.

You see them near the bores, sitting in trees, or near the dams. Or near the waterhole, where the water is in the creek.

It has sharp feathers on his head similar to the crested pigeon. It has a bit of red and a bit of yellow. It is very beautiful.

They eat the seeds of paddy melons and seeds from all kinds of trees such as wild orange. They also eat prickles.

They fly in groups, making a lot of noise.

@graph.name: arleye
@graph.sentence:
Unte arleye aretyeke apmere-arrpe anenhe ikwere. Putye-werne alhemele, anyente apeke, atherre apeke, aw atningke mpwanke apeke.

Kwarte itne mpwareme, atherrke akertneke ware. Kwarte atningke, six pale, eight, aw nine apeke. Atherrke-atherrke mape. Anwerne arleye arlkweme, kwarte-arlke.

Arleye apele thipe akngerre-apenhe anthurre. Re ahelhele ware untentye akngerre. Alkereke irretyeke arrangkwe, ilpelhe urteke anthurre-nge. Brown one, ite arlpentye, blue akweke ware, ite ikwerenhe.

Re pwelerte anthurre unteme nanthe-nge anpere anthurre.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
You see emus all over the place. When you go bush, there might be one, or perhaps two, or a whole lot of them.

It lays its eggs just on the grass. There are many eggs, sometimes six, eight or nine perhaps. They are green in colour. We eat the emu, also the eggs.

The emu is a very big bird. It just runs on the plain. It doesn't fly in the sky, its wings are too short. It is brown in colour, with a long neck and a little bit of blue around the neck.

When he runs very fast, he's faster than a horse.

@graph.name: arlpatye
@graph.sentence:
Atherrke-atherrke, untye ikwerenhe untarne-untarne. Kaperte urrperle, atnertenge kwene-urlkere urrperle. Tayele ikwerenhe blue akweke. Thipe mwerre akngerre anthurre.

Itne ntange artetye-arenye arlkweme, ante arne arrpenhe mape-entyele. Itne antywe mpwareme utnantheke, aw apereke apeke, ulte kweneke.

Tyerrtye mapele arlpatye arlkwentye akngerre. Kere anwerne-kenhe, kere putye-arenye.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
It is green, and its neck is yellow. Its head is black, and there is black on its belly. It has a bit of blue in its tail. It is a beautiful bird.

They eat mulga seeds and seeds from other trees as well. They make their nest in the gidgee tree or in the hollow of a river gum.

People eat ring-necked parrots. It is our meat, our bush meat.

@graph.name: arrewelkere
@graph.sentence:
Thipe arrewelkere arerle, atningke anthurre anerlenge, kwatye itwele. Kwatye awenge itwele, dam itwele, bore-ke arlke arerle. Angkemele anerrirrerlenge. Apurte akwete alkererle alherlenge aretyeke.

Thipe intelhentye, kwerte- kwerte mperlkere ante athetheke spot akweke, inngerrele, untarne-untarne akweke ware. Kaperte ikwerenhe arrirlpe, pelkere- arteke akine.

Itne ntange atherrke arlkweme, aw ahelheke aremele apeke. Itne antywe itne-kenhe mpwareme. Arne antyerrke akertneke, ulte kweneke, kwarte arlke.

Tyerrtyele renhe arlkwentye akngerre, kere anwerne-kenhe.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
You see big mobs of cockatiels sitting close to the water. Near the waterhole and the dam, and you also see them at the bores. All sitting around talking. They are always in a group when they are flying.

They are multicoloured birds, with pale blue-grey smoky colour and a bit of white, and small red spots on the face, with bits of yellow. They have a feather crest on their head, similar to the Crested pigeon.

They eat seeds from the grass or whenever they see them on the ground. They make their nest in a hollow of a tree and their eggs are there.

People eat cockatiels, that's our meat.

By Therese Ryder

@graph.name: arrpwere
@graph.sentence:
Thipe arrpwere apele urrperle ante mperlkere. Thipe teye-teye-arteke kene renhe aretyeke, rarle akngerre-ulkere arle.

Arne akngerre akertneke renhe arerle-anerlenge. Angkerlenge renhe awetyeke, angkentye mwerre akngerre anthurre. Putyele apeke intemele you renhe awerle ingweleme anthurre angkerlenge.

Ahelhele alherlenge renhe arerle, apmwe akwekeke apeke, aw tyape akweke arne kwene-arenyeke apeke, arlkwetyenhenge. Itne antywe itne-kenhe mpwareme apere ulte kweneke, kwarte ikwerenhe arlke.

Thipe arrpwere anwerne arlkwentye akngerre kwenye, kere anwerne- kenhe anetyakenhe arle re.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
The magpie is black and white. He looks like the magpie-lark, but is a bit bigger.

You see him sitting up in a big tree. When he sings he makes a lovely sound. When you're out in the bush you hear them singing early in the morning.

When he walks around on the ground he is looking for grubs in logs, or little snakes, for food to eat. These birds make nests in the hollows of gumtrees and that’s where they lay their eggs.

We don't eat him, he's not our meat.

@graph.name: artapwe-artapwe
@graph.sentence:
Artapwe-artapwe - irretye mape arteke akine renhe aretyeke. Re kere arlkweme. Kere akweke mape nhenge athakwere, kelyawe, ankerte apeke, arlewatyerre apeke. Ante re arlkweme, merne ngkweltye aremele ahelheke, iwerreke arle.

Antywe re mpwareme, arne akweke mape inemele, arne akertneke mpwareme, irretyele-arteke akine.

Putyenge ure akngerre ampeme, unte aretyeke artapwe-artapwe mape, alkerele untherlenge. Urele arle ampeke kere mape arlkwetyeke.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
The black kite is in the wedge-tailed eagle family. It eats meat. It eats mice,  lizards cadneys, goannas It eats bits of food scattered on the ground after people have been eating.

It makes its nest out of little sticks high in a big tree just like wedge-tailed eagles.

When you see bush fires burning you see lots of black kites  flying around. They eat anything that gets burnt in the fire.

@graph.name: artetyerretyerr
@graph.sentence:
Thipe artetyerretyerre unte aretyeke, urrperle, tayele arlpentye, ante inwenge mperlkere.

Renhe angkerlenge awerle, akngerre anthurre. Re apeke ngkwenge ileme, arne iwenhe apeke renhe aremele. Apmwe apeke aremele, aw unte apeke apmere kwenele aneme, re ilelheme rarle akethele anemele.

Re arlkweme intelyapelyape akweke, tyape aparre ahelhe-arenye, ante alkereke-irrentye akngerre itne arlwentye akngerre mape.

Antywe ikwerenhe re mpwareme arneke arlpare anetyeke yakwethe akweke arteke, kwarte ikwerenhe arlke. Anwerne artetyeretyerre arlkwentye akngerre kwenye.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
You see the Willy Wagtail, it is black in colour, long tail and white breast.

When they talk they talk real loud. It tells you about anything that it sees. Maybe it sees a snake, or if you are inside the house he's telling you he's outside there.

He eats small butterflies, grubs that live in the ground and any kind of insects that fly around.

It makes its nest, it looks like a little bag hanging in the tree, for its eggs. We would never eat the willy wagtail bird.

@graph.name: artewe
@graph.sentence:
Artewe apele anwerne arlkweme, kere anwerne-kenhe. Arrekwelenyele arle arlkwerretyarte.

Kwatye akngerre-iperre aretyeke atherrke akngerre taym atningke anthurre. Nameke ntange arlkwerlenge. Re tyerrtye mape aremele, ite arlpentye irremele. Re parrpe akngerre alheme atere-atere irremele re alkereke irremele unteme.

Kwarte re mpwareme atherrke kweneke ware. Ante re arlkweme antelyapelyape akweke mape, tyape akweke atherrke kweneke arlke, apmwe akweke, aw kelyawe akweke mape arlke. Artewe apele, playne akngerre-arenye.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
We eat the bush turkey, it is our meat. Old people used to eat it in the old days.

After the big rain when there is a lot of grass, you see a big mob of them. They eat grass seeds. When they see people, he stretches his neck long. He hurries along looking scared, he flies away into the sky.

It lays eggs in the grass. It feeds on little butterflies, little caterpillars from underneath the grass, little snakes and little lizards. It lives on the open plain.

@graph.name: atetherre
@graph.sentence:
Thipe atetherre apele apmere Central Australia-ke aretyeke, apmere arrpanenheke.

Kwatyeke itne irrperreme, atningke anthurre, apurte irremele. Alkererele alherlenge arerle, apurte mpwanke.

Itne ntange ahelheke aremele arlkweme. Itne antywe mpwareme ulte kweneke, arne akertneke.

Thipe atetherre tyerrtyele arlkweme, kere anwerne-kenhe. Arrekwelenyele arle arlkwerretyarte.

Thipe atetherre kwenhe atherrke-atherrke mape.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
Budgerigars live in Central Australia and are seen all over the place.

They come to the water as one big group. You see them flying in one big group.

They see seeds on the ground and eat them They make a nest in a hollow up high in a tree.

People eat budgerigars, it's meat that we eat. Old people in the early days used to eat them.

Budgerigars are green in colour.

@graph.name: ilentye
@graph.sentence:
Ilentye mape aretyeke, apmere arrpanenheke, town-ke apeke, park mapeke arlke arerle. Apmere putye-werne alhemele, atningke anthurre arerle.

Unte apeke lherele apeke interle, kele unte aretyeke ilentye mape apere akertnele anerlenge, ingwele arlke. Ratye-irrerlenge yanhe unte aweme, wale iwenhenge apekarle itne alakenhe irremenge unte know-im-iletyeke.

Tyerrtye apeke lherele apetyeme kele unte mwantye anetyeke, aw akngwelye arlke apeke. Unte nhenge akarre anetyeke mpwareme.

Ilentyele merne ntange arle atningke arlkwentye akngerre arne-arenye ntange ahelheke arlkweme pateyemalene ntange arlke. Itne apere ultele aneme, antywe kwenele.

Ilentye kwenhe anwerne arlkwentye akngerre, anwerne- kenhe kere.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
You see galahs all over the town and in all the parks. When you go out in the bush you see big mobs of them.

When you camp in the creekbed you see the galahs sitting up in the gumtrees, even at night. If you hear them being disturbed, well you will know something is around. 

Maybe someone is walking in the riverbed. Then you need to look out, there may be danger coming, possibly a dingo. It makes you stay awake.

Galahs they eat big mobs of seeds. They eat seeds from the trees and from the ground and also the seeds of the paddy melon. Their nest is in the hollow of a gum tree.

We eat galahs, they are our bush tucker.

@graph.name: irrarnte
@graph.sentence:
Irrarnte mape apele apmere arrpanenheke aretyeke putye-werne alhemele. Apurte mpwanke anerlenge aw alkerele alherlenge, angkerremele.

Thipe urreye-kenhe tayele aretyeke, athetheke. Kenhe marle-kenhe tele akenhe untarne-untarne arle. Thipe mwerre akngerre mape.

Apere ulteke itne antywe itne-kenhe mpwareme, kwarte itnekenhe arlke. Itne-kenhe ntange akenhe pateyemalene, ante itne lyeke arlkwentye akngerre, merne itne-kenhe.

Irrarnte anwerne arlkweme, kere anwerne-kenhe.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
When you go out bush you see the Red-tailed Black Cockatoo all over the place. They talk, talk, talk when they fly along in a group.

You see the male one's tail, it is red. And the female bird's tail is yellow. They are beautiful birds.

Its nest is in the river red gum, it makes it there to lay its eggs. It eats paddy melon seeds, and also all kinds of prickles, that's its food.

We eat the Red-tailed Black Cockatoo, it's our meat.

@graph.name: irretye
@graph.sentence:
Thipe irretye apele akngerre apenhe anthurre. Re apwerte akertne anthurreke, antywe mpwareme, aw arne akngerre anthurreke apeke.

Re arlkweme rapete aw naneyekwete akweke aw pweleke akweke apeke aremele.

Apwerte akertne anthurre-werne alkereke-irremele imarte kere renhe akngirtnemele arlkwetyeke, aw akwerrke ikwerenhe apeke wantetyeke.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
The wedge-tailed eagle is a very big bird. It makes its nest on top of the hill, or in a big tree.

It catches rabbits, small nanny-goats or small bullocks, when it sees them.

It flies up to the top of the hill and takes the meat back to eat, and to feed its babies.

@graph.name: irrkerlantye
@graph.sentence:
Irrkerlantye anyente ikwele tnerle-anentye akngerre. Kere ikwerenheke apeke unthemele.

Kere ikwerenhe re areme, kelyawe apeke, ankerte apeke aw arlewatyerre apeke, athakwere arlke, re iparrpe akngerre kwene-irremele, antirrkwemele imarte arlkwemele.

Thipe irrpikwe renhe, re ite ultakeme. Thipe arrpenhe areye akenhe ikwere-ketye atere-irreme.

Re antywe ikwerenhe arne antyerrkeke mpwareme irretyele arteke akine.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
When the falcon flies it stands in one place in the sky. He’s looking down on the ground for a feed.

If he sees a lizard, or a cadney or a goanna or a mouse he flies down very quickly, snatches them and then eats them.

If it sees other birds it will break their neck. Other birds are frightened of it.

It makes its nest from dry sticks, like the eagle does.

@graph.name: kwerrkwerrke
@graph.sentence:
Putyele intemele you awerle kwerrkwerrke angkerlenge, arne akertnenge.

Ampe mape atere-irrentye akngerre. Ampe mapele aweme, itne arrangkewarreme. Meye itne-kenhe ileme, itne apeke arnterre-anthurre angkerlenge arlkerrirlenge arlke.

Meyele ilem, ‘Ampe areyaye! Nterte-irraye! Arrantherre yanhe aweme? Arrantherre arle arnterre angkeme kwenhe, yanhe apetyeme. arrenhe-antherrenhe arlkwetyeke.’ Kele itne atere ankwe-irreme.

Kwerrkwerrkele kelyawe arlkweme, athakwere apmwe akweke, ante ingwele untentye akngerre mape. Ante anwerne kwerrkwerrke arlkwentye akngerre kwenye, kere anwerne- kenhe anetyakenhe.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
When you sleep out in the bush you hear that boobook talking, up in the tree.

Children get very frightened. They hear that and they start crying. Their mother tells them off if they make too much noise or scream out.

The mother says, ‘Hey kids! Keep quiet! You hear that? You mob making too much noise, that’s why he’s coming. ‘You-know-who’ is coming to eat you mob!’ They get frightened and go to sleep.

The boobook eats lizards, mice, little snakes and things that go around in the night. And we don’t eat the boobook – it’s not our meat.

@graph.name: lperrpaye
@graph.sentence:
Thipe lperrpaye mape unte aretyeke itnenhe kaperte thayete urrpele. Akwete-akwete apurte akwete arlkerele alherlenge.

Atherrke tayme unte aretyeke. Atherrke akngerre-ntyele alkereke irrerlenge.

Apurte akwete, imarte alkereke irremele, awethe kene imarte ahelheke arrernelhemele.

Itne antywe itne-kenhe mpwareme arne antyerrke ulteke-arleke. Kwarte arlke ikwerenhe mpwareme.

Lperrpaye mape anwerne arlkwentye akngerre kwenye, kere anwerne-kenhe anetyakenhe.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
You see the woodswallow has black on its face. They fly around in a group, again and again.

You see them in the green time after rain. They fly around where it is green.

They form a group and then fly around, then they all land together on the ground again.

They make their nests out of dry sticks. They make it for their eggs.

We never eat the woodswallows, they are not one of our meat foods.

@graph.name: lyerre-lyerre
@graph.sentence:
Thipe lyerre-lyerre apele thipe akweke anthurre mape.

Putye-werne alhemele you arerle arne akertneke atningke anthurre angkerremele anerrirrerlenge. Alkereke imarte irremele apurte akwete arne arrpenhe-werne anteme unterlenge.

Ntange itne ahelheke kutyemele arlkweme, merne itne-kenhe. Kwatyeke irrperreme, antywe itne mpwareme arne akertneke. Utnanthe ulteke-arleke aw antywe itne arneke-arleke, artetyerretyerr-kenhe- arteke akine.

Ante anwerne lyerre-lyerre arlkwentye akngerre kwenye, kere anetyakenhe.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
The variegated fairy wren is one of the small birds.

When you go bush you see them up in the trees, a big mob of them all talking. Then they fly away in a group from one tree to another.

They eat grass seeds from the ground, that's their food. They gather near water, and they make nests up in the trees. They make their nests in the sides of the bushes, similar to the willy wagtail.

We never eat wrens, they are not meat for us.

@graph.name: mekalhampwe
@graph.sentence:
Thipe mekelhampwe, kaperte, thayete urrperle, tayele arlpentye akngerre.

Antywe ikwerenhe mpwareme arne akngerre akertneke. Re itwerle anemele arerle anemele, itepe arrpe anenhe, ampe apeke apetyeme-ketye antywe ikwerenhe ultaketyeke.

Antywe ikwerenhe re mpwareme arne, ngkweltye-ngkweltye mape-ngetyele ware. Arne mape aw manterre ngkweltye mape inemele. Thipe-kenhe ilpelhe-ngentyele inemele atyete mpwaremele kwarteke, ante thipe akweke ikwerenhe anetyeke.

Renhe putyeke ware aretyeke, itne apmere itwewerne apetyentye akngerre kwenye.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
The Black-faced cuckoo shrike has black around the eyes and a long tail.

It makes a nest in a big tree. It sits up near the nest, looking around everywhere, in case kids come too close and break its nest.

It gathers up bits of sticks for its nest and gathers bits of old material or bird feathers laying around to make the nest soft for its eggs and for the baby birds to sit in.

You only see them in the bush, they don't come close to houses.

@graph.name: mpernpe
@graph.sentence:
Thipe mpernpe apele, thipe akweke. Kwerte-kwerte, atnerte kwene thayte mperlkere, ite kwene thayte mperlkere. Alknge urrperle. Alkngenge akertne thayte untarne- untarne, arrakerte untarne-untarne, ingke ikwerenhe untarne-untarne. Tayele arlpentye akngerre.

Re tyape arlkweme, aw arne akweke arrpenhe mape alkerele alherlenge. Ntange itne arlkwentye akngerre mape arlke.

Antywe itne mpwareme arne akertneke, kwarte arlke.

Anwerne mpernpe arlkwentye akngerre kwenye. Kere anetyakenhe.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
The yellow-throated miner is a small bird. It is grey, with white on the underneath of its belly, and under its neck. Its eye is black. Just above the eye is yellow its beak is yellow and its feet are yellow. It has a long tail.

It eats grubs, or any flying insects living around plants. It also eats different kinds of seeds.

It makes a nest up the tree, for its eggs.

We don't eat these birds, they are not our meat.

By Therese Ryder

@graph.name: nturrerte
@graph.sentence:
Thipe nturrerte apele, unte aretyeke, apwerte akertneke. Apwerte aywerte-aywerte, nhenge-ulkereke.

Untarne-untarne, inwenge mperlkere, urrperle intelhentye akerte, ante akaperte arrirlpe. Thipe akweke mwerre akngerre anthurre.

Apurte akwete itne, aywerte kwene-werne untheme. Apwerteke ware itne akwete itne-kenhe mpwareme. Aywerte kweneke apeke.

Tyerrtyele arlkweme kene nturrerte, pelkere-arteke akine.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
The spinifex pigeon you will see up on the rock. It is from the spinifex covered hills.

It is an orange-yellow colour, with white on the chest with a black stripe, and a crest on its head. It is a beautiful small bird.

They run all together into the spinifex, they lay their eggs on the rocky ground, among the spinifex.

People also eat spinifex pigeon, same like the crested pigeon.

@graph.name: ntyerlpenye
@graph.sentence:
Ntyerlpenye apele thipe ahelhe playne- arenye. Re antywe mpwareme, atherrke atnartengeke.

Kwarte apeke ikwerenhe aneme, ante ampe apeke, arelhe apeke apetyeme, re arne antyerrke akertnele anemele areme.

Tyerrtye apeke antywe ikwerenhe-warne apetyeme-ketye, kwarte ikwerenhe inetyeke.

Itne apeke anpere alheme, kele re ahelhe-werne atnarnpeme atnarnpemele unteme antywe ikwere-werne kwarte akertnele artepe anetyeke.

Re arlkweme tyape aparre, ahelhe-arenye intelyapelyape akweke apeke, aw insect akweke mape. Tyerrtyele renhe arlkwentye akngerre kwenye.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
The pipit belongs to the plain country. It makes his nest in amongst the green grass.

When it’s got eggs in the nest, if a kid or a woman comes past its nest it flies up to a dry stick and sits down and watches them.

It makes sure that people don’t come near its nest and take its eggs.

If they go past it jumps down to the ground, jumps down and runs to its nest and sits on top of its eggs.

It eats a kind of caterpillar that lives in the ground,  and little butterflies maybe or little insects. But people don't eat pipits.

@graph.name: nyingke
@graph.sentence:
Nyingke mape aretyeke apmere putyeke. Atningke anthurre. Thipe akweke mape inwenge mperlkere, brown akweke ware, ulte kwenhe theyetele mperlkere dot akweke mape-akerte. Arrakerte ikwerenhe, akenhe, athetheke arle.

Desert-werne apeke arle unte alheme, itne ngkwenge kwatye imerneme, kwatyeke apeke arrangkwe anerlenge. Itne ntange atherrkeke arleke aremele, arlkwentye-akngerre, ahelheke arlke kutyemele, kwatye arlke antywemele.

Itne antywe mpwareme arne akwekeke, aw atnyemeke apeke aw arlketyerreke apeke, untyeyeke arleke apeke, kwarte ikwerenhe arlke.

Nyingke, tyerrtye akngerre pate mapele arlkwetyarte. Anwerne arlkwentye akngerrentye, kere anwerne-kenhe.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
You see zebra finches in the bush. Biggest mob. Its a small bird, white belly with a little bit of brown under the wings and lots of little white dots. It has a red beak.

Anytime you go out bush they are around water, they can show you where the water is. You see them in the green time feeding in the bushes and on the ground, also around the water.

The birds make their nest in a little tree, or in the witchetty bush, the dead finish tree or the corkwood, for its eggs.

All the old people used to eat zebra finches. We ate them, they were our meat.

@graph.name: parlkene
@graph.sentence:
Parlkene apele kookaburra arteke kene, rante-rante anthurre. Wale parlkene arle akweke ulkere arle.

Apmere tywerretye arenye arle. Kookaburra arteke kene, apmwe akweke arlkwentye akngerre kelyawe akweke arlke.

Lhere arnkeke alhwenge mpwareme antywe ikwerenhe mpwareme alhenge kweneke, kwarte ante thipe akweke ikwerenhe.

Anwerne parlkene arlkwentye akngerre kwenye.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
The kingfisher is like a kookaburra, it looks similar. But the kingfisher is smaller.

It lives in the open country. Like the kookaburra it eats small snakes and lizards.

It makes a hole in the bank of the creek and makes its nest inside the burrow, for its eggs and little baby birds.

We don't eat kingfishers.

@graph.name: pelkere
@graph.sentence:
Thipe pelkere.
The Crested Pidgeon.
Thipe pelkere apele untyeye-ke antywa mpwarentye-akngerre, kwarte ikwerenhe arlke.
The Crested Pidgeon makes its nest in the corkwood tree. for its eggs.
Pelkere-rele ntange arlkweme, atherrkeke,  ahelheke kwetyemele, ntange itne arlkwentye akngerre mape.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
The Crested Pidgeon eats seeds from the grass, picking them up from the ground.
Pelkere kwenhe tyerrtye mapele arlkweme, kere anwerne-kenhe. Arrwekerlenye arle arlkwetyarte.
People eat pidgeons it's our meat. Old people used to eat them in the past.

@graph.name: teye-teye
@graph.sentence:
Thipe teye-teye.
Thipe teye-teye apele  unte aretyeke, mperlkere ante urrperle.
Arrpwere arteke kene, rarle akweke-ulkere arle.
Antywe ilkwerenhe mpwareme, ahelhe-urrknge-ngentyele arne akertne anthurreke kwarte ikwerenhe arlke.
Re tyape aperre ahelheke aremele arlkweme antelyapelyape akweke.
Kwatyeke re irrpeme, kwatye antyweme.
Thipe teye-teye kwenhe anwerne arlkwentye akngerre kwenye.
Anwernekenhe kere anetyekenhe kwenhe re aneme.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
Peewee.
The peewee bird, you see that it is black and white.
It is similar to the magpie, but it is a bit smaller.
It makes a nest ?from the ground high in a tree for its eggs.
It looks for caterpillars on the ground to eat, and for small butterflies.
It goes into the water and drinks.
We don't eat the peewee.
It is not one of our meat foods.

@graph.name: tirre-tirre
@graph.sentence:
Tirre-tirre. Thipe lherele anentye akngerre, kwatye awenge itwerle. Re lhere arnkareke antywe ikwerenhe mpwareme, parlkenele arteke kene.
Re peye arlkweme, aw arne akweke arkereke irrentye akngerre mape. Tyape akweke, ahelheke inemele re arlkweme, antelyapelyape akweke mape arlke.
Renhe aretyeke intelhentye yelawe wan, pelewe arlke arrakerte urrperle, arrakerte arrirlpe. Tayle arlpentye.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
Rainbow bee-eater. This bird lives along the river bed where there is water. It makes its nest in the creek bank, just like kingfishers do.
It eats bees, or anything that flies around. little grubs that it finds in the ground, it eats, and any little moths or butterflies.
It has many colours, yellow and blue. It has a long black beak and a long tail.

@graph.name: tyewaketye
@graph.sentence:
Thipe tyawaketye apele urrperle ante mpwerlkere, urntane-urntane akweke.

Unte itnenhenhe aretyeke, apurte akwete arlkerele alherlenge. Arne akertne werne atheke antyenemele walye mape akertneke, aternkemele, atheke-irremele, angkerremele.

Apurte akwete arne arrpenhe werne anteme arlkereke irremele.

Itne arlkweme tyape akweke, irrkngelhe kwene ante intelyapelyape akweke mape, ahelhe kwene arenge tyape akweke aperre mape. 

Anwerne tyewaketye arlkwentye akngerre kwenye.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
The babbler is black and white with a bit of brown.

You see them always flying around in groups. They move around under the tree then they climb up the tree, jumping and rushing around talking.

All together in a group they fly to another tree.

They eat little grubs from under the bark of a tree, insects flying around under the tree and little grubs from under the ground.

We don’t eat the babbler bird.

By Therese Ryder

@graph.name: urelyarre
@graph.sentence:
Thipe urelyarre apele unte aretyeke, kwete-kwete, alknge iterele akenhe untane-untane arle. Urrperle akweke artepe ikwerenhele. Mperlkere akweke mape ilpelhe akertnel, arrakerte pelkere arteke kene.

Antywe ikwerenhe re mpwareme atherrke-ngentyele ware, pelkerele arteke kene, kwarte arlke.

Renhe angkerlenge unte awetyeke arntepe arteke kene.

Re arlkweme ntange ahelheke aremele aw atherrkeke arlke.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
You can see the diamond dove is a smoky grey colour and around its eye is a reddish colour. It is darker on its back. On the back of its wings you see a lot of white dots and its beak looks like the crested pigeon's.

It makes its nest from bits of grass like the crested pigeon does, for its eggs.

It makes a sound you can hear it, a bit like a peaceful dove.

It eats seeds that it finds on the ground and in the grass.

By Therese Ryder

@graph.name: uringe
@graph.sentence:
Thipe uringe. Uringe alengke anthurre iwelhentye akngerre, nhenge tyerrtyele apeke ampele apeke areme-ketye.

Arne akertnele em anerle, parrape aretye-akenhe anthurre ilelhemele. nhenge tyerrtye arle apeke ampele arlke areme-ketyenge.

Arne antyerrke arteke em anerle-anerle, akngelhetye-akenhe anthurre, nhenge tyerretyele arlke ampele arlke aretyekenhe anetyenhenge. Itne arne kwele aretyenhenge.
@graph.sentenceTranslation:
The tawny frogmouth is well camouflaged, so people and children can't see it.

It sits up in a tree and doesn't show itself and people and children can't notice it.

It sits there like a dry stick, not moving, so people and children can't see it. They think it's just a stick.
